05358nam a2200865Ia 9780271084121DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20192019pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710841217 a10.1515/97802710841212doi  a(DE-B1597)583635  a(OCoLC)1269268909  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aBIO0220002bisacsh04a946/.0530922231 aMitchell, Silvia Z., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aQueen, Mother, and Stateswoman :bMariana of Austria and the Government of Spain /cSilvia Z. Mitchell. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (312 p.) :b10 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes on Names -- tAbbreviations -- tDynastic Chart -- tIntroduction: The Historical and International Significance of Mariana’s Regency -- t1. A Habsburg Destiny, 1634–1665 -- t2. Mariana’s Court and Political System, 1665–1667 -- t3. Resolving Philip IV’s Legacy, 1665–1668 -- t4. Consolidating Power at Home, 1668–1670 -- t5. At the Pinnacle of Power, 1670 to November 5, 1675 -- t6. The Politics of Motherhood, November 6, 1675, to 1677 -- t7. Reconciliation, Vindication, Triumph, 1678–1679 -- tConclusion: Mariana’s Historical Legacy -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhen Philip IV of Spain died in 1665, his heir, Carlos II, was three years old. In addition to this looming dynastic crisis, decades of enormous military commitments had left Spain a virtually bankrupt state with vulnerable frontiers and a depleted army. In Silvia Z. Mitchell’s revisionist account, Queen, Mother, and Stateswoman, Queen Regent Mariana of Austria emerges as a towering figure at court and on the international stage, while her key collaborators—the secretaries, ministers, and diplomats who have previously been ignored or undervalued—take their rightful place in history.Mitchell provides a nuanced account of Mariana of Austria’s ten-year regency (1665–75) of the global Spanish Empire and examines her subsequent role as queen mother. Drawing from previously unmined primary sources, including Council of State deliberations, diplomatic correspondence, Mariana’s and Carlos’s letters, royal household papers, manuscripts, and legal documents, Mitchell describes how, over the course of her regency, Mariana led the monarchy out of danger and helped redefine the military and diplomatic blocs of Europe in Spain’s favor. She follows Mariana’s exile from court and recounts how the dowager queen used her extensive connections and diplomatic experience to move the negotiations for her son’s marriage forward, effectively exploiting the process to regain her position.A new narrative of the Spanish Habsburg monarchy in the later seventeenth century, this volume advances our knowledge of women’s legitimate political entitlement in the early modern period. It will be welcomed by scholars and students of queenship, women’s studies, and early modern Spain.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aQueenszSpainvBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Women.2bisacsh  a1621-1665.  a1665-1700.  aCarlos II (1665-1700).  aDiplomatic history.  aDiplomatic relations.  aEspaña.  aHabsburg.  aHistoria 1665-1700.  aKing of Spain.  aMariana of Austria (1634-1696).  aMariana of Austria.  aMonarchy.  aMonarquía.  aQueen.  aRegents.  aSpain Seventeenth century.  aSpain history.  aSpain.  aconsort of Philip IV.  aforeign relations.  amother of Carlos II.  aqueen mothers.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z97831107